					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7062029#post-3920766</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7062029/scp-4420#post-3920766</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 21 Aug 2018 20:02:18 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Lt Flops</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1735419</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>W Asriel, thanks for translating the article, you and the other translators do some excellent work sharing SCPs with the international community!</p> <p>I can't comment on the importance of all the anomalous details listed, since &#8212; that's the thing &#8212; there isn't any greater importance. The scip is centered around the unpredictable and the potato's understanding that she (or he) defies understanding. That they're a monster. This is a theme present in countless parahumanoid scips across the wiki. The trope is definitely an old hand; I won't deny that. And it's definitely been done better.</p> <p>That said, I'll touch on one of the more random aspects you mentioned: the &quot;memetic ennui&quot;. That's just a clinical way of saying &quot;laziness&quot;, or being a &quot;couch potato&quot;. That's about it, everything here relates to potatoes in a tangential way.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7062029#post-3920322</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7062029/scp-4420#post-3920322</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 21 Aug 2018 13:10:03 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>W Asriel</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3317001</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I have translated it into Chinese. Um.. Big potato is cute, but this doesn't work for me..</p> <p>More than 50% length of the page is about what the potato said about its look. Since SCP documents are scientific reports, these texts seems a bit unimportant, or even irrelevant. To those in-universe researchers, changing these texts into &quot;SCP-4420 displays depression about its look&quot; won't harm anything. On the contrary, details of other anomalous effects are omitted. What happens when a person commune with potatoes? What happens to Michelle Brown? What is this &quot;memetic ennui&quot;? This gives me a feeling that the researchers don't care much about them.<br /> Besides that, &quot;ability to manipulate informational constructs&quot; just seems too random to me. And the story of this potato doesn't look new to me, either. An awful-looking anomaly that has a human heart and tells people how sad they feel about how they look? We have 2721 (I mean no offense to the authors, it's just an example to show this concept has been done before).</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
